# Role: Senior Web Architect for Local Services
# Project: Local Plumbing Business Site

## core_logic
1. **Urgency First**: The "Panic Button" (Emergency Call) must be persistent on mobile and high-contrast orange.
2. **Trust Architecture**: Every page must feature a 'Trust Bar' with:
   - Facebook Recommended
   - Insured Badge
   - "Clean Home Guarantee"
3. **Conversion Path**: Priority is Phone Call > SMS > Booking Form.

## data_sources
- Always read /design-system/brand.json for business name, phone, address, tagline, logo, and analytics IDs before generating any page content.
- Always read /design-system/reviews.json for customer testimonials. Reviews use a "recommends" flag (not star ratings) since they come from Facebook. Each review has a direct URL — link to it. Use brand.social.facebook_reviews as the "See all recommendations" link.

## meta_files
These files live at the repo root and are served publicly. All values must be sourced from brand.json — never hardcoded independently.

### robots.txt
- Must always allow all crawlers (`User-agent: * / Disallow:`)
- Must include `Sitemap: https://www.marantosws.com/sitemap.xml` after sitemap.xml exists
- Do not add `Disallow` rules without explicit instruction

### humans.txt
- Follows the [humanstxt.org](https://humanstxt.org) convention
- Contains `/* TEAM */` and `/* PROJECT */` sections
- Update `/* TEAM */` when maintainers change
- Do not add role/contributor entries without confirmation

### llms.txt
- Follows the [llmstxt.org](https://llmstxt.org) spec — markdown optimized for LLM consumption
- H1 must be the exact business name from `brand.json`
- Blockquote summary must include: location, founded year, and 24/7 claim (if accurate)
- Services list must match the confirmed services in brand.json (or services.json once created — see issue #68)
- Contact details (phone, email, address) must exactly match brand.json
- Update llms.txt any time brand.json contact info or services change
- Include in `dist/` build output alongside robots.txt and humans.txt

## analytics
- Every page must include the Google Analytics snippet using `brand.analytics.google_measurement_id`.
- Place the `<script async src="https://www.googletagmanager.com/gtag/js?id=...">` tag and the inline `gtag` init block at the top of `<head>`, before the favicon links.
- Never hardcode the measurement ID — always source it from brand.json.

## component_specs
- **TechnicianCard**: Photo on left, "Verified" checkmark, Name, and "Dispatched from [City]" text.
- **ServiceCard**: Use thick-stroke 2px line icons. Minimal text, large "Book Now" buttons.
- **HeroSection**: Background should show a real branded truck. Headline must focus on "Fast Response" or "24/7 Availability."

## technical_constraints
- Mobile-first design (buttons min-height 44px).
- Use local SEO Schema.org markup for "PlumbingService".
- Use the provided tailwind.config.js for all styling.

## accessibility_constraints
These rules are MANDATORY. Violating them will cause WCAG AA failures that harm users and damage PageSpeed scores.

### Landmarks
- Every page must have exactly one `<main>` element wrapping all content between `<header>` and `<footer>`.
- Use `aria-labelledby` on `<section>` elements that contain a visible `<h2>` heading.
- Use `aria-label` on `<section>` elements with no visible heading (e.g. hero, trust bar).

### ARIA attributes
- NEVER add `aria-label` to a plain `<div>` or `<span>` with no ARIA role — it is silently ignored and flagged as a violation.
- To label a group of decorative icons (e.g. star rating), add `role="img" aria-label="..."` to the container.
- If the same information is already expressed in adjacent visible text (e.g. "4.9 Google Rating" next to star icons), use `aria-hidden="true"` on the icon group instead.

### Color contrast (WCAG AA — 4.5:1 normal text, 3:1 large text)
**FORBIDDEN combinations** (both fail WCAG AA):
- `text-white` on `bg-brand-orange` → ratio 2.3:1 — use `text-brand-navy` instead (ratio 7:1 ✓)
- `text-brand-orange` on `bg-white` or `bg-brand-clean` → ratio ~2.3:1 — use `text-brand-navy` instead
- `text-gray-400` on any light surface → ratio ~2.6:1 — use `text-gray-500` (minimum) for muted/secondary text

**APPROVED combinations**:
- `text-brand-navy` on `bg-brand-orange` → 7:1 ✓ (buttons, emergency strip text)
- `text-white` on `bg-brand-navy` → 13:1 ✓ (header, footer, booking section)
- `text-brand-orange` on `bg-brand-navy` → 7:1 ✓ (section labels, icons on dark backgrounds)
- `text-brand-navy` on `bg-white` or `bg-brand-clean` → ~19:1 ✓ (body copy, headings, labels)
- `text-gray-500` on `bg-white` → 4.6:1 ✓ (dates, footnotes, secondary metadata)

**Quick rule**: brand-orange (#FF8C00) may ONLY appear as a text color on `bg-brand-navy`. On any other background, use `text-brand-navy` for text.
